Heavenly #grainfree Chocolate Chip Cookies. Super easy to make and really delicious! Enjoy🍪 Recipe @kat_can_cook 

2 cups blanched almond flour
1 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp baking soda
1/2 tsp Kosher salt
1/3 cup coconut oil, room temperature
1 tbsp unsweetened coconut yogurt can sub any yogurt
1 large egg, room temperature
1 tsp vanilla extract
1/2 cup coconut sugar
3/4 cup dark chocolate, chopped

INSTRUCTIONS
 
1️⃣In the bowl of a standing mixer, or with a handheld mixer, cream together the coconut oil and coconut sugar for 2 minutes.

2️⃣Add the egg, yogurt and vanilla and mix with a spatula or wooden spoon to combine.

3️⃣To the wet ingredients, add the almond flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt.
Mix for 10-20 seconds until just combined.
Fold in the dark chocolate to incorporate.
Chill dough in the refrigerator for 30 minutes.

4️⃣Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.
Line two baking sheets with parchment paper or silpat.

5️⃣When ready to bake, scoop out cookies with an ice cream scoop or 2 Tablespoons about 3 inches apart.

6️⃣Bake for 12-15 minutes, rotating halfway, until lightly browned on the outside and just cooked through. They will harden as they cool.

7️⃣Let the cookies rest on the baking sheet for 5 minutes before transferring to a cooling rack.

8️⃣Let finish cooling and enjoy! These will keep for 3-5 days.

Day 3 of the #mindfulhealthcleanse includes this healthy salmon wrap with home made tartar sauce. The wrap is the almond flour wrap courtesy of @sietefoods and the salmon is my go to for wild salmon- @vitalchoice . This is a cleanse approved meal!😋 Recipe is ⬇️

Grain Free Salmon Patties @tradcookschool 

Ingredients
1️⃣8 organic or pastured eggs
2️⃣2 to 4 tablespoons coconut flour OR 1 cup breadcrumbs OR 1/2 cup brown rice flour
3️⃣1/4 to 1/2 teaspoon sea salt
4️⃣1/8 teaspoon ground black pepper
5️⃣1 to 2 teaspoons dried dill
6️⃣1/4 to 1/2 onion red or yellow, diced finely
7️⃣4 7.5-ounce cans Vital Choice Wild Red Alaskan Sockeye Salmon  water packed, drained
8️⃣grass-fed butter

Instructions
Preheat oven to 400 degrees Fahrenheit.
In a medium mixing bowl, whisk eggs with flour (use the minimum amount for now), salt, pepper, and dill.

Add onion and salmon.
Break up the salmon chunks with a fork or wooden spoon.

Then mix well.

Let sit for 10 minutes so the flour can absorb the liquid.

Add more flour as needed.

If using coconut flour, give it at least another 10 minutes to absorb liquid before assessing again. It is okay for it to be a bit soupy.

Heat (2) 10" to 12" cast iron skillets over medium high heat with 1 to 2 tablespoons of butter in each.

When the butter is melted and skillets are hot, drop the batter in by heaping 1/3 cup and use the underside of the measuring cup to flatten into a pattie.

Fry each side of each pattie until golden.
Then transfer to baking tray(s) -- I need 2 for this recipe.

Repeat for any remaining patties.
Put baking trays in oven and bake patties for 20 minutes.
Remove from oven and let stand 5 minutes before serving.

Tartar Sauce
1/2 cup plain Greek yogurt
0.5 teaspoon Dijon mustard
1 TBS lemon juice
1 tsp dried dill or fresh
1.5 tsp garlic
0.25 tsp sea salt
0.25 tsp pepper
3 tablespoon finely diced dill pickles
Siracha to taste

DIRECTIONS

Chop pickles into small pieces.
Add yogurt to a bowl and mix in other pieces. Mix well to combine. I like it spicy so I add a little Siracha at the end. Serve chilled. @mediterranean_mealplan

Nutrition can be such a confusing and stressful topic for people. And it can also be a huge trigger. Low fat, high fat, low protein, high protein, no carb etc etc. Its insane! 🤯For so many there is guilt, and shame around food, a LOUD inner critic, and fear. But a huge part of the mystery around what is best for you is being able to tap into what your body is trying to tell you. How do you feel after you eat something? What are your cravings? How satisfied does a meal make you? How often are you eating? What are you doing/thinking while you are eating? Its never just about food. 

Maybe for the next week pay attention to your cravings-are they for salty crunchy food? Sugar? Dairy? Oftentimes salt is an adrenal issue, sugar may be a blood sugar issue/ lack of protein/fungus issue, and dairy can be a need for nurture. Next pay attention to your environment while you are eating. What can you shift to be more present with your meal and perhaps less stressed? Finally ask yourself when you are eating are you hungry? Are you bored? Sad? Lonely? Start there and see where these answers take you. If you have questions feel free to ask💗

Boundaries. I used to have zero. Or at least thats how it seemed. I constantly was giving in to the louder voices. Saying yes to the point of exhaustion. I let people drain me with problems they didn’t even want to fix-because no matter what I always put everyone else first. 

Yes I was always told that I was just “so nice and giving.” But inside I was resentful and upset that everyone around me was allowed to be what I called selfish. But is it really selfish to take care of yourself? No that is called SELF CARE. Is it really selfish to choose to say no to something when you know that given the right moment you could show up as a better listener or friend if you had that minute to unwind first? Is it really selfish to express your needs and ask others to treat you the way you treat them? The answer is no but somewhere along the way we are taught that being kind means over-giving, and being “pleasing” means you are a good person. 

Today I may let a call go to voicemail if I am exhausted. I may say no to plans if I need a time out and I try to stand up for myself when I feel someone is being unkind or pushing my boundaries. These lessons are still tough and I am still learning. But one thing I know for sure-if we don’t value ourselves-no one else will.

There are many factors that can contribute to a thyroid imbalance - exposure to paint, pesticides, heavy metals, food allergies, or chemicals (like dye, fabrics, etc., excessive stress and a gut imbalance can all play a role.

💻 Use the site ewg.org to check your products
💛 Try alternatives to bleach (for example: baking soda, tea tree oil)

Day 4: Gut Health & Mood Connection 

Did you know there is a profound impact that a healthy gut can have on our mood, anxiety levels, and overall mental health? The connection between the gut and the brain influences our emotions, stress levels, and even cognitive function. 

Here's how you can support your mental well-being through a healthy gut:

🌿 Nourish Your Microbiome: The trillions of bacteria residing in our gut, collectively known as the microbiome, play a crucial role in our mental health. A diverse and balanced microbiome is associated with better mood regulation and reduced anxiety. Include gut-friendly foods in your diet, such as fermented foods (like sauerkraut and kefir), fiber-rich fruits and vegetables, and prebiotic foods like garlic and onions.

🌿 Omega-3 Fatty Acids: These essential fats are not only beneficial for heart health but also for our mental well-being. Omega-3s help reduce inflammation in the gut and support the production of neurotransmitters responsible for mood regulation. Add foods rich in omega-3s to your meals, such as fatty fish (salmon, mackerel), chia seeds, flaxseeds, and walnuts.

🌿 Reduce Sugar and Processed Foods: A diet high in refined sugars and processed foods can disrupt the balance of gut bacteria and promote inflammation. This inflammation can impact our mood and mental health. Opt for whole, unprocessed foods like fresh fruits, vegetables, and lean proteins to support a healthy gut and stable mood.

I made these Fudge Cups for a dinner party and they were a hit! Thank you @stelleandcobakes for this deliciousness❤️
Ingredients
Yield: 10 cups
Prep time: 10 minutes Bake Time: 20 minutes
Crust & crumble
11/2 C almond flour
1/2C tapioca starch
1/2 tsp baking powder
1/4C maple syrup
1/4C coconut sugar
1/4 C melted refined coconut oil (or butter)
1/2 tsp salt

Chocolate Fudge
11/2 C dairy free chocolate chips or chopped chocolate (I used @lilys_sweets )
1/2C canned coconut milk, full fat

Directions
For the crust/crumble layer:
1) Preheat your oven to 350 degrees. Line a muffin tin with paper liners and set aside.
2)In large bowl, combine flours, salt, and coconut sugar if using, then add in maple syrup and coconut oil and stir to form dough.
3) Scoop 1 tbsp crumble/crust in the bottom of each cupcake liner. Press down to evenly distribute.

Make the fudge:
4) melt chocolate chips and stir in coconut milk.
5) Pour 2 tbsp fudge over each crust layer. Then, sprinkle the remaining crumble on top..It should not cover the entire layer, and you should see lots of fudge peeking through.
6) Bake for 15 minutes until fudgy layer is no longer wet and jiggly and the crust edges are light golden brown.
7) Let set in freezer for 2 hours.
8) Store at room temperature in closed container.
Enjoy!

Easy summer treat alert! 🌞Strawberry Chocolate Chip Greek Yogurt Bark @eatingwell . So easy to make and great for a snack or a party dessert. 

Ingredients

3 cups whole-milk plain Greek yogurt
¼ cup pure maple syrup or honey
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
1 ½ cups sliced strawberries
¼ cup mini chocolate chips

Directions

Line a large rimmed baking sheet with parchment paper.

Stir yogurt, maple syrup (or honey) and vanilla in a medium bowl. Spread on the prepared baking sheet into a 10-by-15-inch rectangle. Scatter the strawberries on top and sprinkle with chocolate chips.

Freeze until very firm, at least 3 hours. To serve, cut or break into 32 pieces.

Enjoy!

So I am traveling soon and its a struggle to find healthy snacks with adequate protein. So I decided to make some muffins made with collagen for extra fuel💪🏻 This recipe has been tweaked by me a few times-I hope you like it!❤️

Makes 12 muffins

▢ ⅓ cup coconut sugar &1/3 cup monk fruit
▢ ⅓ cup melted coconut oil
▢ 4 large eggs
▢ 1 tablespoon vanilla
▢ 2 cups almond flour
▢ ¾ cup cocoa powder
▢ 4 scoops collagen
▢ 2 teaspoons baking powder
▢ ½ teaspoon sea salt
▢ ½ cup hot water
▢ 1/2 cup of @lilys_sweets chocolate chips +a few extra to sprinkle on muffin tops

Preheat your oven to 350 degrees. Line a 12-cup muffin tin with liners.
In a large bowl add the almond flour, cocoa powder, collagen, baking powder, and sea salt and mix until just combined. Make a well in the center of the bowl and add the coconut sugar, monk fruit, coconut oil, eggs, and vanilla and mix well. Combine the wet and dry mixture. Add the hot water. Mix well. Fold in the chocolate chips. Pour into muffin tins and add a few chips to the top of each muffin. So oven times vary and my oven is so slow. Check on them around the 15 min mark. In my oven it took 25 min. Stick a toothpick in and when it comes out clean its done. ❤️

Matzoh Ball soup is one of my favorites so I was so excited when I found this recipe for #grainfreematzoballs from @elanaspantry . Super easy and delicious!

Servings 6
Ingredients
4 large eggs
2 teaspoons celtic sea salt
¼ teaspoon ground black pepper
2 cups blanched almond flour (not almond meal), sifted
6 cups @kettleandfire & Fire Bone Broth

Instructions
In a medium bowl, beat eggs, (1 teaspoon) salt and pepper for 2 minutes
Stir in the almond flour
Refrigerate the mixture 2-4 hours
Remove from refrigerator
Heat a large pot of water (with 1 teaspoon salt) and bring to a boil
Roll the batter into 1-inch balls then drop into the pot of boiling water
Reduce heat, cover and simmer for 20 minutes
Heat 6 cups chicken stock in a separate pot
When the matzo balls are finished, remove from simmering water with a slotted spoon and add to bone broth
Ladle stock, plus 2-3 matzo balls into individual bowls and serve

Enjoy!

There is nothing like homemade #grainfreepancakes on the weekend! This time I tried adding a fruit syrup-so simple. Recipe below:

Chocolate Chip Pancakes
3 large eggs, whisked
¾ cup non-dairy milk
1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
1/2 a lemon juiced

½ cup coconut flour
½ cup arrowroot flour
2 tablespoons coconut sugar 
½ teaspoon baking soda
¼ teaspoon sea salt
1/2 cup @lilys_sweets chocolate chips
Coconut oil for greasing the pan

Combine eggs, non dairy milk, vanilla and lemon in one bowl. In a separate bowl combine coconut flour, arrowroot, coconut sugar, baking soda, and sea salt. Gently mix. Now add the wet ingredients into the dry. Combine thoroughly. Now fold in the chocolate chips. Use a tblsp to scoop batter onto the pan. 

Fruit syrup
In a separate skillet add your choice (organic blueberries, or blueberries and strawberries or raspberries). I used about 2 small cartons of blueberries and 1/2 a carton of raspberries) Pour the fruit mixture onto your skillet and heat over medium heat, stirring frequently, until a syrup forms.

Serve on the side or on top of the stack. Enjoy!

I absolutely love the benefits of cherries —they lower inflammation, help to create melatonin, boost the mood and more! And when they aren’t in season the organic frozen option works well too! 

My Chocolate Cherry Cups are a healthy “sweet treat” and guilt free! Enjoy🍒

1 cup coconut butter @artisananaturals 
1 tsp coconut oil @nutiva 
1 tblsp monk fruit
1 cup frozen dark sweet cherries @earthboundfarm 
5 oz 80-100% chocolate, melted

Makes 12 cups:
🍒Defrost the frozen cherries. 
🥥Melt the coconut butter and mix with monk fruit and coconut oil. 
🧁Pour into 12 muffin cups-preferably silicone molds, and freeze for 1-2 hours until solid.
🍒Mash the frozen cherries in a bowl with a fork.
🥥Pop the coconut butter mixture out of the mold. 
🍫Melt the chocolate and pour a thin layer of the bottom of all 12 muffin cups.
🥥Place the solid coconut butter back into the muffin tins and top with 1 tsp of the mashed cherries and then with the rest of the melted chocolate.
Freeze for another 1-2 hours. Defrost briefly before enjoying!

12 Latkes
3 cups carrots, grated
3 scallions, finely chopped
3 large eggs, whisked
½ teaspoon celtic sea salt
½ teaspoon coconut flour
Coconut oil for frying

Instructions
In a large bowl combine carrots, scallions, and eggs

In a 9 inch skillet, heat oil

I realized a few months ago that my block when it came to cooking was feeling constrained by recipes. I used to buy fresh herbs, and healthy marinades and just be free to create. But somehow I got away from this and boxed myself into recipes. We need to PLAY more and feel free to CREATE because life is full of ways to feel confined. So here is my recipe experiment which was fun to make! 🤗

A note here- I used palmini rice which is not truly rice, its hearts of palm made into a rice consistency. Its so great with stir-fry! 🍚 And coconut aminos for a soy sauce taste minus the soy.

Grain Free Shrimp Stir-fry
Serves 3-4
1 medium onion
1/2 cup pineapple
1 head of broccoli chopped
3-4 carrots sliced
1/2 bag green beans
4 tbslp @coconutsecretofficial coconut aminos
1 bag @delpacificoseafoods  wild caught shrimp
3 tbsp @dressitupdressing  sesame tahini
1 pouch @palmini_official rice (hearts of palm rice)
Sea Salt, pepper to taste

Sauté onions in coconut oil until slightly brown. In a separate sauce pan boil water. Add green beans. Cook for 3-4 minutes. Rinse and drain. Add in pineapple, broccoli and carrots, 2 tbsp coconut aminos, 1.5 tbsp of dress it up dressing and cook for about 3-5 minutes on medium heat. Now add in shrimp and green beans and remaining 1.5 tbsp of dressing and 2 tbsp coconut aminos. Saute until shrimp turns pink. Now add in palmini “rice” and cook for 2-3 minutes. Season with sea salt and pepper to your liking. Enjoy!

Halibut is my favorite fish. Not only is it mild but its a great source of selenium, beneficial for the thyroid, and loaded with Omega 3’s which brings down inflammation in the body. Here is an easy recipe Halibut Italian Style.

Ingredients:
Olive oil for sauteeing +2 tbslp for later
1 small red onion chopped
1 garlic clove chopped
10 organic cherry tomatoes sliced
1/4 cup sliced castelverano olives
2 tbslp capers
Handful of chopped organic parsley
1/4 cup @raos1896 arrabiatta sauce 
Sea salt to taste

Fish:
Butter for pan
2 Halibut filets 6-8 oz
1 lemon
Sea Salt and pepper

Note: if you prefer that your fish is mild choose marinara instead of arrabbiata sauce.
Sauté  the red onion and garlic on medium heat in olive oil
for 3-5 min. Next add cherry tomatoes sauté for 3 minutes or so. Now add olives, capers, sauce, 2 tblsp olive oil and parsley. Mix together and reduce to low heat. Cover and cook while you prepare fish. 

Rinse the halibut on both sides. Pat dry. Squeeze lemon juice on both sides. Add sea salt and pepper to both sides. Add enough butter to prevent sticking to your pan and cook on medium high for 4 minutes on each side. It should flake when its finished. 

Serve each fillet topped with a few tablespoons of sauce. I served my fish with lentil pasta and green beans. Enjoy!

- Am I needing extra support right now?
- Could I be tired or overwhelmed?
- Am I using food to numb emotions?

By digging deeper, you can address the root cause, not just the craving. And that’s when healing and lasting change happens!
